Research error handling quality metrics and anti-patterns across multiple programming languages, focusing on patterns detectable by static analysis. Document the taxonomy of error handling anti-patterns: swallowed exceptions (catch with empty body or only logging), overly broad exception catching (catching Exception or Throwable in Java, bare except in Python), error codes ignored at call sites, panic usage in Rust or Go where errors should propagate, converting errors to strings and losing structured error information, and inconsistent error handling within the same codebase. For each language, document the idiomatic error handling pattern: Java checked exceptions and the debate over their utility, Python's EAFP versus LBYL styles, Go's explicit error return values and the common patterns for wrapping them, Rust's Result and ? operator, Ruby's rescue and the difference from exception abuse, and C++ exception safety guarantees. Research whether error handling quality metrics correlate with system reliability — find empirical studies on exception handling bugs as a fraction of total production bugs. Look for the Nakshatri et al. (2016) study on exception handling in Java and similar work. Also research how tools like PMD, Checkstyle, and SonarQube implement error handling rules and what their false positive rates look like. Document which patterns are unambiguously bad (empty catch blocks) versus context-dependent (broad exception catching in top-level handlers).
